title: Mini mudguard for Cube Stereo Pro rear suspension
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
I recently got a Cube Stereo Pro mountainbike, but while riding there is always mud splashing against the rear shock.

There is a part for the job made by Cube, but where's the fun in buying??
So I designed this.
It's in two parts for better printability.

Update: I changed the length of the lower part and increased its radius around the axis, because it could hit the wheel and crack, when using the full suspension travel.

Update 2: New revision, this time i broke it myself.

Notes:

Print the parts standing upright.

To keep the part definitely on the bed, I used a raft with zero Z distance to the part, basically a several layer thick brim, or a small board for the part to stand on and be attached to.

I recommend ABS for its flexibility and toughness (it's quite a tight fit, and it is on a MTB^^).

Use high temperatures for good layer adhesion, as this part is quite long but thin (-> lever).

Update: To prevent cracks between layers I acetone vapor treated the part.

description.text:
Used on 1"x1" square aluminum with rounded edges.  
Has not been tested.  
Print two and connect using .25" bolts.  
Created by FRC Team 2470

I made this mount to work with the range of 808 cameras (that I have a few of). This makes a sturdy protective mount. Designed to be screwed directly onto the rocket using small tapered screws, there’s a curvature for most body tubes so I would suggest using good double stick tape on the edges of the mount along with the screws.

The thicker (15mm) 808 cameras snap in place and really don't need anything to contain them but the thinner ones (13mm) need to be fastened using small nylon zip ties.

Unloading the video from the camera requires removal of the camera from the mount . I could make an opening for the USB port(s) but in the end felt there were too many different types of cables to try and accommodate.

With version 2 I added a slot on the base that will allow you to use a large nylon zip tie to temporarily attach it to your air frame. BUT NOTE - if you look at the image, I over tightened this mount without support under it and the plastic broke away a little. If you use double stick tape to compensate for the curve of the body tube and don't over tighten it, this problem shouldn't occur.

comments.text: I definitely would add snap on mounts for different body tubes if you can manage it.  Some of my flights saw the camera totally dislodged from the ejection charge or if you lose part of the rocket.  I love the case.  It's very compact.
comments.author: SkyRider

comments.text: There is such a wide range of body tubes, I figured I would leave it (for now) with the screw mounts stabilized by double stick tape. But I'll look at other ways to fasten it to the air frame.

comments.text: You could probably use rail button fasteners to hold the mount to the tube, so long as it is conformal.  The nut plate goes inside the tube and you could glue that in.  The part of the nut plate sticking through the tube would be recessed into the mount.  You should only need one nut plate if you are conformed to the tube.

Mind you I would use a thinner double stick tape or spend more time cutting it to the contour of the tube.   The basic idea was that the mount was (mostly) permanent.    That said, I may add to this a series of contour plates using some basic tube sizes.

These dentures were designed for my chickens. I'm planning on them being able to hunt larger animals like feral cats, raccoons, possums,coyote, and deer.

The next part is VERY IMPORTANT: the dentist will need to tape the beak shut and the tape will have to stay there for at least one hour for the cement to set-up. description.text:
This is a powerfull bowden extruder with a 2:1 reduction ratio. It uses a special drivegear running on a ball bearing and the filament is guided through a PTFE (teflon) tubule.
With a 2A NEMA17 steppermotor we measure a pulling force of above 7000 pond (ca. 69 Newton).

Driver.stl should not be printed. It has to be made of brass or steel.

printed parts:
attached stl, except driver.stl

other materials:

1 special drivegear made of brass rod 10mm diameter, 30mm length,
1 ball bearing 683,
1 ball bearing 608,
1 ball bearing 625,
2 screws m3 x 50mm,
4 screws m3 x 45mm (you can shorten 50mm ones),
1 setscrew m8x16,
1 setscrew m3x6,
6 plain steel washers m3,
1 rivet nut 5mm, m3
1 countersunk screw m3x12,
2 short extruder springs (id>3mm, len can 10mm, wire about 0.5mm),
1 push in fitting 4mm/m5,
1 RAMPA insert 8x8xM5,
1 piece of PFTE tubing, od=3mm, id=2mm, length ca. 30mm,
1 stepper motor NEMA17, the stronger the better

For looking nicer and better strenghtness, my parts (except the gear set, because of the precision loss) are finished with acetone, but it's not really necessary.
The big gear is pressed on the filament driver and locked with the m3 setscrew (not as deep, dont block it on the axis). The small gear ist only pressed on the 5mm motor shaft.
It is intended for use on a flat shaft. If your motor shaft is not flatted, you can ream the gear to 5mm and insert a m3 nut.

Machining the filament driver:
Cut a 30mm piece of a 10 mm brass rod.
Drill a centered 3mm hole through the full length.
Drill a centered 7mm hole, depth 4mm on one end.
Insert the 683 bearing.
Mount the part on your mill or lathe and machine the hobbing at a distance (center of hobbing) of 6mm from the 'bearing end' of the part. Therefore use an m6 tap.
Drill the 2.5mm fixation for the big gear at a distance of 5mm from the opposite end of the part (non bearing end) an tap it to m3.
Press the big gear on the non bearing end of the part and your filament driver is ready to use.

Prepare the tighter:
Remove the support (axis for 625 bearing) with a small plier.
Drill the 625 bearing axis hole to 3mm.
Drill the bottom side of this hole to 5mm (leave the upper unchanged).
Countersink the 3mm and the 5mm side of this drilling.
Insert the 625 bearing.
Insert the rivet nut, fix it with the countersunk screw m3x12,
Tap the two holes of the compression counterpart (8x15 rounded small part from tighter2) to m3. Insert this part into the tighter (maybe you have to ream the insert to 8mm).
Drill the two holes of the other (flat) small part to 3mm.
Put the springs on the m3x50 Bolts.
Put a washer on each m3x50 bolt.
Put the flat small printed part (from tighter2) on the m3x50 bolts.
Insert the bolts into the rounded small part from tighter2.
Now the spring loaded extruder lock is prepared.

Preparing the Idler:
Ream the filament channel to 3mm.
Drill the axis mount to 3mm.
Insert the PTFE tubing into the filament channel.
Screw the RAMPA insert in place.
Insert the push in fitting into the RAMPA insert.
While doing so, the PTFE tubing will be pushed a bit forward.
Dont cut it off yet.
Insert the 608 Bearing, fix it with the M8 setscrew.

Mount the extruder:
Put three m3x45 bolts through the "deckel" part (leave the low mount free).
Put the tighter2 part on the two bolts in the connected deep mounts of the 'deckel' part.
Put the idler part on the third bolt.
Fix this assembly to the NEMA17 motor.
Put the prepared filamentdriver in ist place (dont forget the bearing) and insert the fourth m3x45 bolt.
Review the PTFE insert. Shorten it If neccessary, but leave it as long as possible.
This will be very useful if you want to print elastic filaments like TPU.
Try to minimize the gap between Filament driver and PTFE inlay.

Finetune the pressing depth of the small gear. This determines the alignment of the filamentdriver to the filament channel. If neccessary use a flat screwdriver and a quick clamp. The gear has to run smooth and the filament has to pass through the center of the hobbing.

description.text:
This is a close to accurate model of a Zamperla Giant Discovery 40 Emergency Brake. When power to the ride is lost a pair of these can be engaged to bring the ride to a stop by clamping down on a brake pad that is attached to the output shift of the reduction box. This is the model we have chosen to release as part of a new tradition that for each new "How Does This Ride Work?" video digital and physical models will be made and one will be released for all to enjoy and use as part of our mission to promote and inspire others to pursue S.T.E.M. and engineering related education.
For the full "How Does a Zamperla Giant Discovery Work?" video with more models and explanation, subscribe to us (it's free) by using this link:
https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCrHzkltKaSHy-v_RESJWizw

Here's a BLTouch Sensor Mount for a Geeetech Rostock 301 mixing printer. The default GTM32 controller does not support auto leveling, but other controllers do. I retrofitted my 301 with Duet WiFi/Duex 5 electronics and a BLTouch and viola! A delta diamond hot end printer with auto-leveling! The mount installs at the rear of the effector. For reference, the probe tip is located at an offset of X=0.00, Y=-45.50, and Z=0.30 from the nozzle. Your Z will vary with your setup somewhat. I've included my config.g, bed.g, and the system macros for deploying, retracting, and reseting the BLTouch for reference if you're using Duet electronics.

You can find the Duet WiFi and its distributors at http://www.duet3d.com

Update 9-28-17: I created Duet macros for the BLTouch and to help in the printer calibration process and I've uploaded them.

Update 10-18-17: Version 2 of the mount has been uploaded! I revised the original design to include some important improvements. First, I improved airflow around the heatsink closest to the probe while still retaining good rigidity in the mount. Second, I added a small slit in the wire retainer to make it possible to install and remove the mount without having to disconnect and reconnect the wires to the BLTouch. Finally, I've found a new friend in Hatchbox Carbon Fiber PLA. It's a perfect filament for a mount like this.

Happy Printing!

description.text:
A ukulele capo based on the design by MarkBenson. Prints in two parts and uses a peg spring for tension.

Update: Now with Fusion 360 file!

Fits a ukulele with a neck up to 37mm wide and around 21mm deep (less if using padding).

I really liked the design of the ukulele capo by MarkBenson, but after printing it I realised that my peg springs don't fit, so I re-built the design in Fusion 360, changed the allowances for the spring, added some extra thickness around the spring to account for the larger spring, and boom - another version!

This new version takes a peg spring with a 7mm coil in the middle, arms approx 17mm long, and made from 2mm wire. Commonly found in NZ.

Spring arm length can be changed by bending the arms to shorten them, which allows the fit between the clamp and the trigger to be adjusted.

Adding soft self-adhesive velcro to the clamping surfaces works well and will help prevent the ukulele and strings from getting scratched.

Printer:

Tarantula

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.3

Infill:

20% Honeycomb

Notes:

My version is printed in PLA at 0.3 res. It probably doesn't matter, but should be printed for strength. I recommend using options like 'detect thin walls' in your slicing program to help strengthen the print.

Check that the printed hole in the trigger is large enough for your chosen spring.

Adding the spring from a clothes peg is relatively simple. I recommend attaching the spring to the body of the capo first, then use pliers to open the spring and attach it to the trigger.

After assembling, if the base of the trigger isn't sitting snugly against the spring, bend the arm of the spring that attaches to the trigger to shorten the distance to the spring coil. It should sit snugly against the coil to prevent it from being too sloppy.

I also recommend adding soft velcro to the clamping surfaces to protect the ukulele and the strings from scratching.
Designed by printing the original design from MarkBenson, drawing up a copy of the design in Fusion 360 using measurements taken from calipers, and then modifying it to suit my requirements.

description.text:
Parametric tool rack I designed. I envision using it for sets of small screwdrivers. You can update for your own settings using customizer.

UPDATE: The new version allows for printing without support, and defining different tool slot diameters per row.

Variables are as follows:
min_height - This is the height of the first row.
height_step - This is how much higher each subsequent row will be. Switch to zero to have the rows level (printable without support).
wall - Thickness of the walls of the tool rack.
rows - Number of rows of tools you want on the rack.
tool_gap - Minimum distance between tool slots (centre to centre, so don't set this smaller than your slot diameters)
slot_diameter - Diameter of the tool slots
tools_odd - Number of tools on odd-numbered rows.
tools_even - number of tools on even-numbered rows.
diameter_by_row - A vector containing the diameter of tool slots row by row. e.g. 12,14,20 would make the first row have a diameter of 12, the second row a diameter of 14 and the third row a diameter of 20. Priority is given to this variable over 'slot_diameter', but it will default to 'slot_diameter' for rows where this isn't defined.

Designed from scratch in openSCAD. I worked out the code for the rows first, then the code for the tool slots.

In the update, I first tried different ways of printing without support, before settling on the incarnation you find here.

Instead of creating a complex multi part piece with moving wheel and so... I've gone for the most simplistic desing to be printed one piece without supports. And I've added some tool holders for basic tools, pliers, and adjustment allen key.

Installation is pretty simple, remove the two corner screws, drop it in, and tighten the screws again.

So, I really liked the design, but I wanted something bigger that I could just fidget with using both hands. I scaled it up about 240% (using Simplify3D I used the manual drag to scale to the approximate size that I wanted). I had some minor issues with assembly because the holes in the ring body didn't scale equally to the size of the pins and gears. To make it all work, I used heat shrink to increase the diameter of the pins for a better fit in the holes of the ring body. They were still a little loose so I used some UV cure cyanoacrylate. I included a picture showing the UV glue under the UV light.

Note that there is an extra spacer ring that I added to fill the gap between the movable ring gear and the retainer ring and glued the 2 pieces together before slipping it over the end and gluing the retainer ring in place.

If you have any questions, feel free to message me.

Also, at some point I'm going to remodel the scaled up version to create snap-fit pins as well as add a bevel to the gears for smoother interaction between the gears.

title: MP Select Mini and Mini v2 Glass Build Plate Etching

description.text: A simple stencil to print onto your glass build plate and cover in Armour Etch. Also included is a laser etchable SVG file. PLEASE READ THE INSTRUCTIONS! The STL File and GCODE are supposed to be a mirror image, in case anyone was concerned.

Step One: Print it!

It is supposed to be a mirror image, so don't freak out. Print this on what your would normally use as the "Back side", and when you flip it over the image will be correct. Put on your glass, apply some water-soluble gluestick (Not necessarily required, but it will turn out better), and print the included GCODE. You can slice it yourself, but the included gcode has some added tweaks and settings that make it print better. Keep in mind that when printing this, you need EXCELLENT build plate adhesion. What the first layer closely. You should manually change the extrusion temperature to whatever you normally use, but keep in mind it does drop 5o after the first layer. Keep the build plate temperature as is! It needs to be hot to create an adequate seal between the plastic.

Step Two: Clean the Glass

After it prints, let it cool down SLOWLY. Once it is cool, rinse under slightly above lukewarm water until all the gluestick is gone, especially in the letters and images. Be careful not to detach any small paces during this process, it will ruin it.

Step Three: Apply The Armour Etch

WARNING: ARMOUR ETCH IS HIGHLY CORROSIVE AND VERY DANGEROUS! WEAR GLOVES AND BE NEARBY A WATER SOURCE! IF YOU DO GET IT ON YOUR SKIN, RINSE YOUR SKIN FOR 15 MINUTES UNDER WATER AND CALL POISON CONTROL! Alright, now that that is out of the way, apply the Armour Etch with a clean paintbrush after shaking the bottle (cap closed, obviously) vigorously for 30 seconds. Apply liberally (to the point where you cant see the glass underneath the cream) and use your brush to make sure it gets into all the nooks and crannies. You can check to see where it is etching by carefully flipping the glass over and seeing where the white cream is touching. DO NOT let it touch any of the glass outside of the stencil. I did, and you can see it in the picture, it left a streak on the side. Looks kind of bad. When you have applied it and are satisfied with how the etch is going to look, let it etch for at least 5 minutes.

Step Four: Rinsing and Cleaning

Take your glass over to the sink, (ANGLE IT AWAY FROM YOU!!!) and rinse all the cream off. From there, take the stencil off, rinse it again to get any cream that may have been stuck and the gluestick under the pieces and dry with a towel. Clean with windex and admire your work.

comments.text:
I use acrylic model paint (mostly Games Workshop or Game Colour/Vallejo)
which you can find in any hobby shop that sells miniatures. Its a
process called drybrushing and its actually quite easy. All you do is
paint the model in a darker shade, then take a lighter shade of the same
color and run the bush on some paper until there isn't much paint left.
Then, whisk the brush across the painted surface. You can do this
multiple times (I usually use 3 or four different shades). Paint applies
to ABS and PLA equally well in my experience. I usually print using
black filament so I don't need to apply a base coat of primer. Hope that
was helpful, but any time you have questions feel free to hit me up!

This a weighted poker card capper. It is placed on your hole cards during a hand to make sure they are not accidentally folded. The base is designed with the same diameter (39mm) as a standard size poker chip so this will stack perfectly on your chips when not in use.

This design is the Aston Villa FC lion logo standing on a ball. The base has "AVFC" text on both sides.

--- Printing ---
1) Print the Lion facing left, so no support material is required. The tabs are only flush with one side to minimize their visibility after assembly.
2) For 2 color base: I only have a single extruder so I set the print to pause at a height of 13.0mm. This allowed me to change to a different color filament for the ball and text on the base.
3) I printed the holder (upside down) and base with line support material spaced at 4.5mm.

--- Assembly ---
1) The holder is designed to have 4 nickels placed inside of it as ballast prior to assembly.
2) The three pieces will slide/snap together.
3) Super glue or another adhesive isn't necessary, but I use a few drops to guarantee it never comes apart.
